- Integrated reset functionality in presenter with proper state management
- Added UI components for reset button with conditional visibility

- Implemented parallel `resetFeatureFlag` method for boolean flags
- Added consistent reset behavior matching platform parameters
- Integrated with existing feature flag UI components

- Added observable fields to manage reset button state (`isResetAvailable`, `isResetButtonActive`)
- Updated layouts to include reset sections for both platform parameters and feature flags

comment.body: It's because the fix is unsafe in the docs: https://biomejs.dev/linter/rules/use-exhaustive-dependencies/ The extension only supports safe fixes on save, which is a good thing. But it does not provide a way to manually apply an unsafe fix. And that's disappointing. I added a feature request to add it this here: https://github.com/biomejs/biome-vscode/issues/751 Once implemented, this would fix the useExhaustiveDependencies case and other similar ones.

issue.title: Allow variables in accessing records data: my_record.$my_var_key

labels.name: needs-triage
labels.description: An issue that hasn't had any proper look

issue.body:
### Related problem

I'm trying to use one universal way of accessing records' data: the dot syntax `record.keyA.keyB`
However, if I get the key name from a variable, this fails since you can't use `record.$var_key_A.keyB`
So the universal beauty of Python doesn't work here `record[var_key_A]['keyB'] = 123`

### Describe the solution you'd like

Allow variables in dot-accessor or add an alternative non-dot syntax:
- record.$var_key_A.keyB
- record.($var_key_A).keyB

Or add an alternative `[]`-like syntax (not sure whether `[]` conflict much, but if they do, could use other alternatives `<>` or `‚Äπ‚Ä∫` or `¬´¬ª` or ..., though the latter are too "quotationally stringy")
- record[$var_key_A][keyB]


### Describe alternatives you've considered

None that are as simple as a single universal method working with strings and variables

### Additional context and details

Similar discussion https://github.com/nushell/nushell/discussions/10472 https://github.com/nushell/nushell/discussions/16453

issue.body:
On my machine (Resonite 2025.6.17.855, ResoniteModLoader 3.0.0), VRCFTReceiver would be loaded by ResoniteModLoader immediately before Resonite initialized the input interface. This caused the driver initialization function to silently fail.

This fix defers driver initialization until after Resonite is fully initialized. The [ResoniteModLoader wiki](https://github.com/resonite-modding-group/ResoniteModLoader/wiki/Creating-Mods#runpostinit) states that the input device setup occurs after `OnEngineInit` and that `Engine.RunPostInit` should be used to register a callback instead.

This change also improves error logging during startup for other unexpected null conditions within FrooxEngine.Engine.

With this fix I was able to get blinking working, but not full eye tracking yet.
